As a whole, Connecticut continues to do well, even in the face of cases on the rise in the city of Danbury. For the first time in a while we arent in the bottom five of New Case Growth Per Capita over the last seven days, but that is likely due to the fact that a number of states are doing well, and Danburys numbers are just enough to throw us off.

Testing remains on its upward track, which is very good given the new arrival of students to many of the colleges who are reopening, and our percent positive is remaining low. Again, the big X factor I dont think is going to be the next couple weeks for students, but rather, the next month or two when things cool off and covid mitigation gets a little laxed when people become more comfortable. Though, my optimisim does still remain.

Watching the US numbers is a little trickier at the moment. New cases had been trending down and now were either at a plateau or a just a blip on the way down. Throwing things off are growing cases in North and South Dakotah who now have the #1 and #2 new case per capita growth in the USA and this is very likely due to the Sturgis bike rally. The big question will be if any of those vectors get brought home from other folks to their repective states.

The positive here is, deaths per day is still under a 1,000 in the seven day rolling average, and testing is on the upswing.
